{"title_page": "UFC Hall of Fame", "text_new": "{{short description|Honors mixed martial artists and MMA personalities}}\n{{Infobox| bodystyle  = class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em; font-size:90%;\"\n| above       = <span style=\"color:#eee;\">UFC Hall of Fame</span>\n| abovestyle  = background-color: #000000\n| subheader   = \n| image1      = [[File:UFC Hall of Fame Logo with drop shadow.svg|225px]]\n| caption1    =\n| headerstyle = background-color: #005AAB\n| header1     = \n| label2      = '''Established'''\n| data2       = November 21, 2003\n| label4      = '''Founder'''\n| data4       = [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n| label5      = '''Inductees'''\n| data5       = 16 pioneers<br> 6 modern-era<br>6 contributors<br>5 Fights<br>(35 total inductees)<br> (3 double inductees)\n| header20    = \n| header30    = \n| header40    = \n| header50    = \n| below       = \n}}\n\nThe '''UFC Hall of Fame''' is a [[hall of fame]] which honors mixed martial artists and MMA personalities, established and maintained by the U.S.-based mixed martial arts promotion [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]. In addition to the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], the UFC Hall of Fame recognizes accomplishments from [[Pride Fighting Championships]], [[World Extreme Cagefighting]] and [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]]; all of which are former mixed martial arts promotions that have been bought-out by the [[UFC]] and its parent corporations.\n\nIt was officially established in Las Vegas on November 21, 2003 at [[UFC 45]] with the inaugural inductees being [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] Originals [[Royce Gracie]] and [[Ken Shamrock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Zuffa-Creates-quotHall-of-Famequot-with-Shamrock-Gracie-Charters-1262 |title=Zuffa Creates \"Hall of Fame\" with Shamrock, Gracie Charters |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2003-11-05 |accessdate=2014-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the UFC announced a significant reboot of its Hall of Fame. The Hall was split into four categories, or wings, and a new class of legends would henceforth be inducted every July at a gala event during the UFC\u2019s annual International Fight Week in Las Vegas.<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2015/5/5/8554521/ufc-revamping-hall-of-fame-planning-to-build-a-physical-location</ref>\n\nThe new wings are:\nModern Era Wing \u2013 for fighters who turned professional after the Unified Rules of MMA were introduced at UFC 28.\nThe Pioneer Era Wing \u2013 for fighters who turned professional before the Unified Rules of MMA were introduced at UFC 28.\nThe Contributors Wing \u2013 for non-participants who made significant contributions to the sport outside of competition \nThe Fight Wing \u2013 honoring specific legendary bouts.\n\nThe new Hall of Fame was a passion project of former UFC executive Anthony Evans, who pitched UFC President Dana White on the four-wing structure several times before finally getting White\u2019s permission in 2015.<ref>https://theathletic.com/1053135/2019/07/01/talking-ufc-hall-of-fames-evolution-with-longtime-staffer-ant-evans/</ref>\n\nIt was also announced in 2015 the UFC would create a physical Hall but, as of 2020, that has not happened.\n\nSince 2015, the UFC Hall of Fame has somewhat gained in prominence and credibility. The company has inducted several more legends who were not on the best of terms with the UFC, including Don Frye and UFC co-creator Art Davie, as well as featured representatives from rival promotions including ONE Championship and Bellator MMA. \n\n==Inductees==\n\n===Pioneer wing===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Date of Induction<br>(event)\n! class=\"unsortable\"| '''UFC recognized accolades'''\n|-\n|[[File:RoyceGracie.png|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Royce Gracie]]\n|November 21, 2003 (''[[UFC 45]]'')\n|{{small|[[UFC 1]] [[List of UFC Champions#Tournament Winners|Tournament Winner]], [[UFC 2]] [[List of UFC Champions#Tournament Winners|Tournament Winner]] and [[UFC 4]] [[List of UFC Champions#Tournament Winners|Tournament Winner]].}}\n|-\n|[[File:Ken Shamrock marines 2005 crop.jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ken Shamrock]]\n|November 21, 2003 (''[[UFC 45]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[List of UFC champions|UFC Superfight Champion]], two UFC Superfight Championship defenses, [[List of UFC champions|UFC 3 Tournament Finalist]], one-time [[List of Pancrase champions|Pancrase Openweight Champion]], one Pancrase Openweight Championship defense and King of Pancrase Tournament Winner.}}\n|-\n|[[File:Dan Severn 52.jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Dan Severn]]\n|April 16, 2005 (''[[UFC 52]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[List of UFC champions|UFC Superfight Champion]], [[List of UFC Champions#UFC Tournaments|UFC 5 Tournament Winner]] and [[List of UFC Champions#UFC Tournaments|Ultimate Ultimate 1995 Tournament Winner]].}}\n|-\n|[[File:Randy Couture by Gage Skidmore.jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Randy Couture]]\n|June 24, 2006 (''[[The Ultimate Fighter 3 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter: Team Ortiz vs. Team Shamrock Finale]]'')\n|{{small|Three-time [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]], three UFC Heavyweight Championship defenses, two-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC Light Heavyweight Champion]], one-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|Interim UFC Light Heavyweight champion]] and [[List of UFC champions#tournament winners|UFC 13 Heavyweight Tournament Champion]]. First fighter to hold two UFC championship titles in two different divisions.}}\n|-\n|[[File:MarkColeman.png|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Mark Coleman]]\n|March 1, 2008 (''[[UFC 82]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]] (first Heavyweight Champion in UFC history), [[UFC 10]] [[List of UFC champions#UFC Tournaments|Tournament Champion]], [[UFC 11]] [[List of UFC champions#UFC Tournaments|Tournament Champion]] and [[Pride Grand Prix 2000 Finals]] [[Tournament]]       [[Champion]].}}\n|-\n|[[File:Chuck Liddell cropped.jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chuck Liddell]]\n|July 11, 2009 (''[[UFC 100]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC Light Heavyweight Champion]] and four UFC Light Heavyweight Championship defenses.}}\n|-\n|[[File:Matt Hughes.png|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]]\n|May 29, 2010 (''[[UFC 114]]'')\n|{{small|Two-time [[UFC Welterweight Championship|UFC Welterweight Champion]] and seven UFC Welterweight Championship defenses.}}\n|-\n|[[File:Tito Ortiz - November 2014 (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tito Ortiz]]\n|July 7, 2012 (''[[UFC 148]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC Light Heavyweight Champion]] and five UFC Light Heavyweight Championship defenses.}}\n|-\n|[[File:PatMiletich.png|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pat Miletich]]\n|July 5, 2014 (''[[UFC 175]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[UFC Welterweight Championship|UFC Welterweight Champion]] (first Welterweight Champion in UFC history), four UFC Welterweight Championship defenses and [[List of UFC champions#tournament winners|UFC 16 Welterweight Tournament Winner]].}}\n|-\n|[[File:Bas Rutten.jpg|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Bas Rutten]]\n|July 11, 2015 (''[[UFC 189]]'')\n|{{small|One-time [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]], one-time [[List of Pancrase champions|Pancrase Openweight Champion]], and two Pancrase Openweight Championship defenses.}}\n|-\n|[[File:Antonio Rodrigo Nogueira \"Minotauro\" Paris - 2004.JPG|100px]]\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ant\u00f4nio Rodrigo Nogueira]]\n|July 10, 2016 (''UFC Fan Expo'')\n|{{small|One-time [[List of PRIDE champions#Heavyweight Championship|Pride Heavyweight Champion]], one-time [[List of PRIDE champions#Heavyweight Championship|Interim Pride Heavyweight Champion]] and one-time [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|Interim UFC Heavyweight Champion]].}}\n|-\n|[[File:Don Frye