9 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony, 2019'')\n|{{Small|One-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC Light Heavyweight Champion]] and [[The Ultimate Fighter 2]] Heavyweight Winner.}}\n|}\n<br />\n\n===Contributors===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Date of Induction<br>(event)\n! class=\"unsortable\"| '''Contributions'''\n|-\n|[[File:TPAR2009.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Charles Lewis Jr.]]<br>(Mask)\n|July 11, 2009 (''[[UFC 100]]'')\n|{{small|Founded the first major mixed martial arts clothing line [[Tapout (clothing brand)|Tapout]].}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Jeff Blatnick]]\n|July 11, 2015 (''[[UFC 189]]'')\n|{{small|Commentator, UFC commissioner and was instrumental in helping the UFC get regulated by athletic commissions.}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Bob Meyrowitz]]\n|July 10, 2016 (''UFC Fan Expo'')\n|{{small|UFC co-creator and owner from UFC 6 to until it was sold to Zuffa in January 2001.}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Joe Silva]]\n|July 6, 2017 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony, 2017'')\n|{{small|UFC matchmaker from 1997 to 2016.}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Bruce Connal]]\n|July 5, 2018 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony, 2018'')\n|{{small|UFC television producer from 1997-2018.}}\n|-\n|[[File:Art Davie - photo credit Art Davie.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Art Davie]]\n|July 5, 2018 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony, 2018'')\n|{{small|UFC co-creator, co-owner from UFC 1 to UFC 5 and first UFC matchmaker.}}\n|}\n\n===Fights===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Fight\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Date of Induction<br>(event)\n! class=\"unsortable\"| '''Notes'''\n|-\n|[[Forrest Griffin]] [[Forrest Griffin vs. Stephan Bonnar|vs]]. [[Stephan Bonnar]] I\n|July 6, 2013\n|{{small|Regarded as the one of the greatest fights in UFC history. Marked a turning point for the UFC in terms of its journey to mainstream acceptance of MMA as a popular, legitimate sport. Forrest Griffin def. Stephan Bonnar by unanimous decision at ''[[The Ultimate Fighter 1 Finale]]''.}}\n|-\n|[[Matt Hughes (fighter)|Matt Hughes]] [[UFC 52|vs]]. [[Frank Trigg]] II\n|July 11, 2015\n|{{small|For the [[List of UFC champions#Welterweight Championship|UFC Welterweight Championship]]. Matt Hughes def. Frank Trigg by submission in Round 1 at ''[[UFC 52]]''.}}\n|-\n|[[Mark Coleman]] [[UFC 17|vs]]. [[Pete Williams (fighter)|Pete Williams]]\n|July 10, 2016\n|{{small|Pete Williams def. Mark Coleman by head-kick KO, the second head-kick KO in UFC history after Gordeau vs Tuli (''[[UFC 1]]'') at ''[[UFC 17]]''. One of the biggest upsets in early UFC history.}}\n|-\n|[[Maur\u00edcio Rua]] [[UFC 139|vs]]. [[Dan Henderson]] I<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ufc.com/news/The-Fight-Henderson-vs-Shogun-I|title=The Fight - Henderson vs. Shogun I|work=UFC|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>\n|July 5, 2018 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony'')\n|{{small|Dan Henderson def. Maur\u00edcio Rua by unanimous decision in a back-and-forth fight at ''[[UFC 139]]''.  Second five-round non-title fight in UFC history and first to go the distance.}}\n|-\n|[[Diego Sanchez]] [[The Ultimate Fighter: United States vs. United Kingdom Finale|vs]]. [[Clay Guida]]\n|July 5, 2019 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony'')\n|{{small|Diego Sanchez def. Clay Guida by split decision in a three round, back-and-forth fight in the lightweight division at ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: United States vs. United Kingdom Finale]]''.}}\n|-\n|[[Jon Jones]] [[UFC 165|vs]]. [[Alexander Gustafsson]]\n|July 9, 2020 (''UFC Hall of Fame Ceremony'')\n|{{small|Jon Jones def. Alexander Gustafsson by unanimous decision in closely fought five-round fight for the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]] at ''[[UFC 165]]''. Fight of the Night.}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ufc.com/ufc-hall-fame UFC Hall of Fame]\n* [http://www.ufc.com/news/ufc-hall-of-fame-2016-media-frequently-asked-questions Hall of Fame FAQs]\n\n{{Ultimate Fighting Championship}}\n{{UFC Hall of Fame}}\n[[Category:Awards established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Sports halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Honors mixed martial artists and MMA personalities}}\n{{Infobox| bodystyle  = class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em; font-size:90%;\"\n| above       = <span style=\"color:#eee;\">UFC Hall of Fame</span>\n| abovestyle  = background-color: #000000\n| subheader   = \n| image1      = [[File:UFC Hall of Fame Logo with drop shadow.svg|225px]]\n| caption1    =\n| headerstyle = background-color: #005AAB\n| header1     = \n| label2      = '''Established'''\n| data2       = November 21, 2003\n| label4      = '''Founder'''\n| data4       = [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n| label5      = '''Inductees'''\n| data5       = 16 pioneers<br> 6 modern-era<br>6 contributors<br>5 Fights<br>(35 total inductees)<br> (3 double inductees)\n| header20    = \n| header30    = \n| header40    = \n| header50    = \n| below       = \n}}\n\nThe '''UFC Hall of Fame''' is a [[hall of fame]] which honors mixed martial artists and MMA personalities, established and maintained by the U.S.-based mixed martial arts promotion [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]. In addition to the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], the UFC Hall of Fame recognizes accomplishments from [[Pride Fighting Championships]], [[World Extreme Cagefighting]] and [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]]; all of which are former mixed martial arts promotions that have been bought-out by the [[UFC]] and its parent corporations.\n\nIt was officially established in Las Vegas on November 21, 2003 at [[UFC 45]] with the inaugural inductees being [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] Originals [[Royce Gracie]] and [[Ken Shamrock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Zuffa-Creates-quotHall-of-Famequot-with-Shamrock-Gracie-Charters-1262 |title=Zuffa Creates \"Hall of Fame\" with Shamrock, Gracie Charters |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2003-11-05 |accessdate=2014-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the UFC announced a significant reboot of its Hall of Fame. The Hall was split into four categories, or wings, and a new class of legends would henceforth be inducted every July at a gala event during the UFC\u2019s annual International Fight Week in Las Vegas.<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2015/5/5/8554521/ufc-revamping-hall-of-fame-planning-to-build-a-physical-location</ref>\n\nThe new wings are:\nModern Era Wing \u2013 for fighters who turned professional after the Unified Rules of MMA were introduced at UFC 28.\nThe Pioneer Era Wing \u2013 for fighters who turned professional before the Unified Rules of MMA were introduced at UFC 28.\nThe Contributors Wing \u2013 for non-participants who made significant contributions to the sport outside of competition \nThe Fight Wing \u2013 honoring specific legendary bouts.\n\nThe new Hall of Fame was a passion project of former UFC executive Anthony Evans, who pitched UFC President Dana White on the four-wing structure several times before finally getting White\u2019s permission in 2015.<ref>https://theathletic.com/1053135/2019/07/01/talking-ufc-hall-of-fames-evolution-with-longtime-staffer-ant-evans/</ref>\n\nIt was also announced in 2015 the UFC would create a physical Hall but, as of 2020, that has not happened.\n\nSince 2015, the UFC Hall of Fame has somewhat gained in prominence and credibility. The company has inducted several more legends who were not on the best of terms with the UFC, including Don Frye and UFC co-creator Art Davie, as well as featured representatives from rival promotions including ONE Championship and Bellator MMA. \n\n==Inductees==\n\n===Pioneer wing===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Date of Induction<br>(event)\n! class=\"unsortable\"| ''